metadata.name: Type-o-Graphic #54
metadata.description:
Type-o-Graphic embraces the ethos of David Carson's groundbreaking graphic design work. It explores the intersections of typography, design, art and chance, harnessing the power of randomness to create a series of posters that are a frenetic celebration of typographic chaos.

This collection is intended to be customized and printed. Your initial thumbnail output is only the beginning ‚Äî several parameters are changeable to find a combination and format to your liking. Please use the keys below to explore the thousands of possible variations within each piece.

Features:
B - Toggle border
N - Change border colour
K - Change background colour (if visible)
T - Toggle top finish (if applicable)
Up/Down - Change colour palette (43)
Left/Right - Change blend modes (20)
L - Change to Landscape
P - Change to Portrait
S - Save image

0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 - Change resolution of image
0 - 600 x 900 - (low-res)
1 - 1200 x 1800 - 4x6" @ 300dpi - (default)
2 - 2400 x 3600 - 8x12" @ 300dpi
3 - 3600 x 5400 ‚Äì 12x18" @ 300dpi
4 - 4800 x 7200 - 16x24" @ 300dpi
5 - 7200 x 10800 - 24x36" @ 300dpi

See accompanying article for more info:
https://www.fxhash.xyz/article/type-o-graphic

Created with p5js by fauxjebus in 2023
Follow me on twitter or instagram @fauxjebus

metadata.name: Divine Levels #30
metadata.description:
The harmonic aspect of the composition is based on the application of various scales and chords - often derived from a central tonality - that are layered and interleaved in a manner similar to the visual shapes of the piece. This creates a constantly shifting harmonic landscape that is both familiar and unpredictable.

The rhythmic element of the composition is based on the layering of multiple polyrhythms, creating a complex and ever-shifting pulse. The polyrhythms are often based on a central pulse that is then layered and interleaved with other polyrhythms to create a complex and dynamic rhythmical landscape.

Overall, the pieces are designed to explore the relationships between shapes, harmonies, and rhythms in a way that is both logical and unexpected. The goal is to create a composition that is both cohesive and unpredictable, allowing for an ever-evolving soundscape of sound and movement.

press s to save png

metadata.name: Qoqnus #64
metadata.description:
Qoqnus

In ancient Greek: œÜŒø·øñŒΩŒπŒæ
In Arabic: Al-Anqa
In English: Phoenix

The sacred bird is a legend that is mentioned in Iranian mythology, Greek mythology, Egyptian mythology, and Chinese mythology.
It is said that he is a rare and lonely bird and does not mate or reproduce. But once every thousand years, it spreads its wings on a large pile of firewood and sings, and when it is excited by its song, it lights a fire with its beak, and by burning in the fire from its ashes, another phoenix is ‚Äã‚Äãborn.
In many cultures, the phoenix is ‚Äã‚Äãconsidered a symbol of immortality, sacrifice and long life.

In this work, I tried to create bird-like shapes that are being formed and created by using a grid in the form of noise and with the shape of rectangles that have random length and width and get their color from the palettes. You can clearly see the wings or the bird's head in most of the exits
In fact, my idea is to depict the moment of resurrection and rebirth of the phoenix from the heart of the ashes, which rises to the sky.
the ash particles around this reborn bird are being scattered in the air and finally from At the heart of this re-creation, a beautiful and glorious phoenix comes into existence.

Made by p5.js

metadata.name: Ichigo #437
metadata.description:
This generator is named 'Ichigo' (Ëã∫/ „ÅÑ„Å°„Åî), the Japanese word for 'strawberry'. 

Seeing each iteration from a suitable distance, small dots (to me, reminiscent of strawberry seeds) overlay different sequences of geometric repetitions, implying a sense of texture, grittiness and irregularity. 

By looking closer however, it becomes apparent to the viewer that the majority of the composition is in fact government by orderly elements, in this case grids of dots. 

This discovery invites the viewer to consider the output in front of them at different levels, near and far. At what point do you feel the dots begin to dissolve into a texture? When do you stop noticing the dots and instead begin to perceive the overall composition?

These questions are posed in a similar fashion as with meditation; at what point does something become something else? When does an in-breath become an out-breath and vice versa? 

Contemplation on simple questions like these can open a small portal into stillness and mindfulness by taking time to slowly observe our responses. 

23 palettes are included, each named after different areas of Tokyo. 

Press 'S' to download a full size 6000px x 6000px PNG output. 

As always, much gratitude and enjoy your piece.

metadata.name: Sketch A #47
metadata.description:
Sketch is an open-ended series. Works evolve as I code a generative project, sometimes drastically. Intermediate works usually don't see the light of day - they get archived and forgotten. This series is snapshots of different forms along the way - each standing alone, but also part of a larger meandering work flow. The word Sketch implies incompleteness. This project may end up being two works, or it could evolve for years. Part of the joy of generative art is never knowing what's around the corner. I have no set schedule. There may be multiple Sketches released a week, or it could be weeks or months between drops. I have no idea where Sketch is heading and there is no guarantee of cohesiveness from Sketch to Sketch. Color palettes and forms will change as new ideas are explored.

Sketch A starts very simple. It's the basic grid framework I intend to use for the series. It's just a simple grid with one colored square (usually). Colors are borrowed from Echos/Orbits. Grid size, padding, and line thickness vary.

metadata.name: aether:Astral Loom #140
metadata.description:
Weaving on the astral plane. Lines of transmission. 
Some journeys are straightforward, others yield a multitude of pathways.
Disconnect to interpret.

(As an experiment) the rarity values assigned to this artwork are completely arbitrary, and are in no way connected to the visual output of the minted piece. One might wonder, why have rarity values at all? That's what I ask myself any time I see a value based on rarity attributes instead of viewer aesthetic. 

That being said, I suppose it's up to each person to decide for themselves the value of art...

This artwork was created using p5js.
